Let’s go through your questions one by one, all in the context of Maven and CI/CD:

1. Public artifact output available in the artifact section and usable by other pipelines?
Yes. In Azure DevOps, when you publish build artifacts (PublishBuildArtifacts@1), they appear in the pipeline’s Artifacts tab.

Other pipelines (release pipelines or downstream builds) can consume these artifacts.

This is separate from Maven repositories — it’s Azure DevOps’ own artifact handling.

2. Workspaces in Jenkins vs Default Working Directory in Azure DevOps
Jenkins workspace → the job’s working directory on the agent, where source code is checked out and builds run.

Azure DevOps $(System.DefaultWorkingDirectory) → the pipeline’s working folder on the agent, where sources are downloaded and tasks execute.

Conceptually they’re the same idea: a per-job working directory on the agent. Just different naming.

3. install moves artifacts to repo?
Yes. mvn install takes the JAR/WAR from target/ and copies it into your local Maven repository (~/.m2/repository).

This makes the artifact available for other Maven projects on the same machine.

It does not push to a remote repo — that requires mvn deploy.

4. Local repo vs remote repo configuration
Local repo → Maven knows the default location (~/.m2/repository), no need to configure in pom.xml.

Remote repo → You must specify the repository URL (and credentials if private) in pom.xml or settings.xml.
Example:

xml
<distributionManagement>
  <repository>
    <id>company-repo</id>
    <url>https://repo.mycompany.com/maven2</url>
  </repository>
</distributionManagement>
5. Maven repos can be used to download artifacts too?
Absolutely. Maven repositories are both sources and destinations:

Download dependencies (e.g., Spring, JUnit).

Upload your own artifacts (via deploy).

6. If source code is in my repo, what is Maven downloading?
Maven downloads dependencies your project needs, as declared in pom.xml.

Example: If your code uses JUnit, Maven fetches junit-4.13.2.jar from Central or a remote repo.

Your source code stays in Git; Maven only pulls external libraries.

7. settings.xml contains remote repo and creds?
Yes. settings.xml is the file Maven uses for:

Remote repository URLs.

Credentials (username/password, tokens).

Mirrors, proxies, profiles.

It’s needed for both downloading dependencies (from private repos) and pushing artifacts (to remote repos).

Without it, Maven can only access the public Central repo.

✅ Summary:

Azure artifacts = pipeline outputs, shareable across pipelines.

Jenkins workspace ≈ Azure DevOps working directory.

install → local repo; deploy → remote repo.

Local repo needs no config; remote repo requires URL + creds.

Maven repos are for both download (dependencies) and upload (your artifacts).

settings.xml is the key file for remote repo access and authentication.

