If source code is in my repo, what is Maven downloading
here junit is the java/maven dependency used for source code testing? means its publicly available right? if i just mention in the pom.xml it can be downloaded? why should i download it from private repo? also central repo means apache maven repo? don't we need to provide creds for that?
Excellent set of questions — let’s unpack them clearly:

🔹 If source code is in my repo, what is Maven downloading?
Maven isn’t downloading your source code — that already lives in Git.
What Maven downloads are the dependencies your project needs, as declared in pom.xml.

Example:

xml
<dependency>
  <groupId>junit</groupId>
  <artifactId>junit</artifactId>
  <version>4.13.2</version>
  <scope>test</scope>
</dependency>
This tells Maven: “I need JUnit 4.13.2 for testing.”

Maven will fetch that JAR from a repository (local cache first, then Central or any configured remote repo).

🔹 JUnit as a dependency
Yes, JUnit is a Java testing framework.

It’s publicly available in the Maven Central Repository.

If you just declare it in pom.xml, Maven automatically downloads it the first time and caches it in your local repo (~/.m2/repository).

🔹 Why download from a private repo?
Central repo is public and contains most open-source libraries.

But companies often host private repositories (Nexus, Artifactory, Azure Artifacts) for:

Proprietary/internal libraries not published to Central.

Third-party libraries with licensing restrictions.

Security reasons (control over which artifacts are allowed).

Faster builds (local mirror of Central).

So you’d use a private repo when you need artifacts that aren’t in Central or when your organization requires it.

🔹 Central Repository
Yes, “Central” means the Apache Maven Central Repository (repo.maven.apache.org).

It’s the default public repo Maven uses if you don’t configure anything else.

No credentials needed — it’s open access for downloading.

Credentials are only required for private repos (to download or deploy).

✅ Summary:

Maven downloads dependencies (like JUnit) from repositories, not your source code.

JUnit is public, so just declaring it in pom.xml is enough — Maven fetches it from Central.

Private repos are used for internal/proprietary artifacts or organizational policies.

Central repo = Apache Maven’s public repo, no creds needed for downloads.

